  "prompt": "Which is better: Less, Compass or Sass?",
  "response": "Each CSS preprocessor (Less, Compass, and Sass) has its strengths, and the \"best\" one depends on your specific project needs. Here's a comparison:\n\nSass (SCSS):\n+ Most popular and widely used\n+ More robust and feature-rich\n+ Extensive library support (like Compass)\n+ Clean, intuitive syntax\n+ Active community and development\n+ Built-in functions and mixins\n+ Works well with modern frameworks\n+ Supports both .sass and .scss syntaxes\n\nLess:\n+ Simpler syntax\n+ JavaScript-based\n+ Easier to learn for beginners\n+ Can be compiled client-side\n+ Lightweight\n+ Compatible with JavaScript libraries\n- Less powerful compared to Sass\n- Smaller community\n- Fewer advanced features\n\nCompass:\n+ Ruby-based framework for Sass\n+ Comprehensive set of mixins\n+ Cross-browser compatibility helpers\n+ Advanced sprite generation\n+ Strong typography tools\n- Becoming less relevant with modern CSS\n- Requires Ruby\n\nRecommendation:\nMost developers prefer Sass (SCSS) today due to its:\n- Comprehensive features\n- Strong community support\n- Compatibility with modern tools\n- Flexibility\n\nModern alternative: Consider PostCSS as a more flexible option.",
